The most important, because the most voluminous and correct, if not the most ancient, manuscript, now remains to be noticed, and which 1 was fortunate enough to discover among the Harleian Manuscripts at the British Museum. Owing to the imperfect classifi· cation of these MSS. towards the end of the last cen· tury, this had remained unknown or unnoticed until I had withdrawn it from its hiding-plaee; classed in the general catalogue immediately under the head of Tna- onoex, and after “ Theophilus ’' the ecclesiastic, is found ‘⁶ Theophilus, monachus;” it has doubtless therefore, been classed with works on theology. It is not men· tioned under the works treating upon the arta, but under the head “Natural Philosophy,’' “Physics,” is found “Theophilus Monachus, de Chemia,” a position in which we should never have expected to find our author upon ‘⁶ The Divers Arts,” and which sufficiently accounts forits neglect¹.
